 for other multifactorials, but this has not come into general use. Another common notation is to place the 



k


{\displaystyle k}

 parameter as a subscript as 



n

!

(
k
)




{\displaystyle n!_{(k)}}

 to denote the multifactorials defined above.
In the same way that 



n
!


{\displaystyle n!}

 is not defined for negative integers, and 



n
!
!


{\displaystyle n!!}

 is not defined for negative even integers, 



n

!

(
k
)




{\displaystyle n!^{(k)}}

 is not defined for negative integers divisible by 



k


{\displaystyle k}

.
Primorial[edit]
The primorial (sequence A002110 in the OEIS) is similar to the factorial, but with the product taken only over the prime numbers.
Superfactorial[edit]
Main article: Large numbers
"N$" redirects here. For the currency, see Namibian dollar.
Neil Sloane and Simon Plouffe defined a superfactorial in The Encyclopedia of Integer Sequences (Academic Press, 1995) to be the product of the first 



n


{\displaystyle n}

 factorials. So the superfactorial of 4 is





sf
⁡
(
4
)
=
1
!
×
2
!
×
3
!
×
4
!
=
288.


{\displaystyle \operatorname {sf} (4)=1!\times 2!\times 3!\times 4!=288.}



In general





sf
⁡
(
n
)
=

∏

k
=
1


n


k
